  <section xml:id="chapter-5-problems">
    <title>Chapter 5 Review Problems</title>
    
    <example>
      <title>Integration Techniques</title>
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          We have learned about four primary techniques of integration this semester:
          <ul>
            <li>Integration by Substitution</li>
            <li>Integration by Parts</li>
            <li>Partial Fraction Decomposition</li>
            <li>Trigonometric Substitution</li>
          </ul>
          Consider the following integral:
          <me>\int \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+9}} \, dx</me>
          In the space below, justify how you would use <em>two</em> of the techniques of integration listed above to solve the given integral. For each technique, you should say in a sentence why the technique is applicable to the given integral, then indicate the first step or substitution that you would use accordingly. You do not need to actually solve the integral using either technique.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                The denominator includes an expression of the form <m>x^2+a^2</m>, where <m>a>0</m>, so we can do a <em>Trigonometric Substitution</em>, using <m>x=a\tan(\theta)</m>. In this instance, <m>a=3</m>, so we substitute <m>x=3\tan(\theta)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The derivative of the argument of the square root is present in the numerator up to a constant multiple, so we can perform an <em>Integration by Substitution</em>. That is, if we differentiate <m>x^2+9</m> with respect to <m>x</m>, we get <m>2x</m>, which is in the numerator if we divide it by the constant <m>2</m>. This allows the <m>u</m>-substitution <m>u=x^2+9</m> to completely rewrite the integral in terms of <m>u</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Without solving for any coefficients, apply partial fraction decomposition to the following rational expression:
          <me>\frac{1}{(x^2+7)(x^2+4x+3)}.</me>
          Your answer should be a sum of fractions whose numerators include coefficients - coefficients you do not need to solve for.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We first factor the denominator. Note that <m>x^2+7</m> is irreducible (it does not factor), while
          <me>x^2+4x+3=(x+3)(x+1).</me>
          So we have
          <me>\frac{1}{(x^2+7)(x^2+4x+3)}=\frac{1}{(x^2+7)(x+3)(x+1)}.</me>
          Now, again since <m>x^2+7</m> is an irreducible quadratic, the numerator of its term in the partial fraction decomposition should have degree one less than the degree of it. That is, the numerator should be degree <m>2-1=1</m>. A general degree 1 polynomial is of the form <m>Ax+B</m>, for some <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. The two linear factors <m>(x+3)</m> and <m>(x+1)</m> are similar. They are degree 1 polynomials, so the numerator of the term in their partial fraction should have degree <m>1-1=0</m>. Degree 0 polynomials are constants, say <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>. This gives the decomposition
          <me>\frac{1}{(x^2+7)(x+3)(x+1)} = \frac{Ax+B}{x^2+7} + \frac{C}{x+3} + \frac{D}{x+1}.</me>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Numerical Methods</title>
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                On the graph of <m>g(x)</m> below, draw the rectangles you would use to approximate <m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{3} g(x)\,dx</m> if you used <em>6 right rectangles of equal width</em>:
              </p>
              <image source="RightRiemannSum.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>A coordinate plane showing a smooth curve labeled g(x). The x-axis is horizontal and marked at 1, 2, and 3, and the y-axis is vertical. The curve decreases from left to right, reaches a minimum slightly to the right of x = 1, and then increases steadily as x approaches 3.</shortdescription>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                On the graph of <m>h(x)</m> below, draw <m>TRAP(5)</m> for <m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^{6} h(x)\,dx</m>:
              </p>
              <image source="TrapezoidSum.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>A coordinate plane showing a smooth, wave-like curve labeled h(x). The x-axis is horizontal and marked at 1 through 6, and the y-axis is vertical. The curve oscillates up and down, with alternating local maxima and minima, while remaining continuous across the interval shown.</shortdescription>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                On the graph of <m>f(x)</m> below, draw rectangles corresponding to <m>MID(3)</m> for <m>\displaystyle \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\,dx</m>:
              </p>
              <image source="MidpointSum.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>A coordinate plane showing a smooth curve labeled f(x). The x-axis is horizontal and marked with points labeled a and b, and the y-axis is vertical. The curve decreases steadily from left to right, starting higher near the y-axis and gradually flattening as it approaches b.</shortdescription>
              </image>
              <p>
                In a complete sentence or two, explain whether <m>MID(3)</m> is an overestimate or an underestimate for <m>\displaystyle \int_{a}^{b} f(x)\,dx</m>. To receive full credit, you should justify your response using properties of the function <m>f(x)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <image source="RightRiemannSumSolution.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>The same graph of g(x) on a coordinate plane, now overlaid with six vertical rectangles representing RIGHT(6), a right Riemann sum from x = 0 to x = 3. Each rectangle’s height is determined by the value of g(x) at the right endpoint of its subinterval. Each rectangle has width 0.5. The rectangles increase in height from left to right, matching the rising portion of the curve, and are shaded to indicate the approximated area under the curve.</shortdescription>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <image source="TrapezoidSumSolution.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>The graph of h(x) on a coordinate plane, overlaid with trapezoids representing TRAP(5), a Riemann sum from x = 1 to x = 6. Each trapezoid has width 1, and its left-side/right-side heights each correspond to the corresponding values of h(x) on the subinterval. The trapezoids vary in height to follow the oscillating shape of the curve and are shaded to show the approximated area under h(x).</shortdescription>
              </image>
            </li>
            <li>
              <image source="MidpointSumSolution.PNG" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>The graph of f(x) on a coordinate plane, overlaid with three vertical rectangles representing MID(3), a midpoint Riemann sum from x=a to x=b. Each rectangle has width approximately 1/3 of the length of the interval from x=a to x=b. Each rectangle’s height is determined by the value of f(x) at the midpoint of its subinterval. The rectangles decrease in height from left to right, reflecting the decreasing behavior of the function, and are shaded to indicate the approximate area under the curve.</shortdescription>
              </image>
              <p>
                The important property of <m>f(x)</m> to leverage is the fact that it is concave up on <m>[a,b]</m>. In particular, the midpoint approximation gives an underestimate when the function is concave up, and an overestimate when it is concave down.
              </p>
              <p>
                Here is some additional commentary on this topic while we are at it. On the other hand, the trapezoidal estimate gives an overestimate when the function is concave up, and an underestimate when it is concave down. Hence midpoint and trapezoidal estimates are kind of "dual" to one another. We can also say that the left and right estimates are "dual" to one another, but in relation to the increasing / decreasing of the function instead of the concavity. To be precise, the right estimate will be an overestimate if the function is increasing, and an underestimate if it is decreasing.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Improper Integrals</title>
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the value of the following improper integral (or show that the integral diverges):
          <me>\int_{10}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^3}\,dx</me>
          <em>Note:</em> Your work will be graded for mathematical accuracy, so be clear and careful about using limit notation as relevant.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \int_{10}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^3}\,dx \amp = \lim_{b\to\infty} \int_{10}^{b}\frac{1}{x^3}\,dx</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \lim_{b\to\infty}\int_{10}^{b}x^{-3}\,dx</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \lim_{b\to\infty}\left[\frac{x^{-2}}{-2}\right]_{10}^{b}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = -\frac12\lim_{b\to\infty}\left(\frac{1}{b^2}-\frac{1}{10^2}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = -\frac12\left(0-\frac{1}{100}\right)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{200}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>
    
    <example>
      <title>Comparison Test for Improper Integrals</title>
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Recall that the integral <m>\displaystyle\int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2}\,dx\lt\infty</m> converges. Consider the following (flawed) justification that the integral diverges, broken into three numbered steps of reasoning:
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Flawed Justification:</em>
          <ol>
            <li>The improper integral <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\,dx</m> diverges since the integrand is of the form <m>\frac{1}{x^p}</m> with <m>p\le 1</m>.</li>
            <li>For <m>x\ge 2</m>, we know that <m>x \lt x^2</m>, so <m>\frac{1}{x} \gt \frac{1}{x^2}</m>. Thus, <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\,dx \gt \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2}\,dx</m>.</li>
            <li>Therefore, by the Comparison Test for Improper Integrals, <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2}\,dx</m> also diverges.</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          In a few complete sentences, identify which step has a flaw and describe the flaw in the reasoning. Note: It is not sufficient to show that the conclusion of the overall justification is false (that is, to prove that <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2}\,dx\lt\infty</m> converges). Rather, you must identify the flaw in the given steps of reasoning.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The flaw is in Step 3. It states that since the larger quantity, <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\,dx</m> diverges, that the smaller quantity <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x^2}\,dx</m> also diverges. However, this is not how the comparison test works. Since <m>\displaystyle \int_{2}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\,dx</m> diverges, we would need to compare to a <em>larger</em> expression/integral in order conclude it also diverges by comparison. Comparing to a smaller expression/integral (as is being done in Step 3) would be inconclusive.
        </p>
      </solution>

    </example>

  </section>

